Vice President Kamala Harris met with President Nana Akufo-Addo in Ghana to discuss various global and regional issues. They highlighted the strong bilateral relationship between the United States and Ghana, focusing on historical, cultural, and economic ties. Harris thanked Akufo-Addo for Ghana's partnership at the United Nations Security Council and its defense of the UN Charter during Russia's war on Ukraine. She also commended Akufo-Addo's leadership in defending and advancing democracy in West Africa. They discussed insecurity in the Sahel region, including the threat posed by extremist groups to Coastal West Africa. Harris announced that the United States would provide over $100 million to support stabilization in Ghana and other neighboring countries. They also discussed Ghana's commitment to economic reforms and debt relief, as well as the importance of people-to-people ties and engagement with the African Diaspora.